        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2926347756" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10609971403129329903">Elbow Room by James Alan McPherson<br/>9 out of 10<br/><br/><br/>Elbow Room is a fantastic collection of stories that has won The Pulitzer Prize, making its great author the first African American to win the coveted award.<br/><br/>In the introduction, James Alan McPherson refers to the fact that in the countryside, people have more Elbow Room and this is where most of the stories the place, outside the cities.<br/>Most of the tales are hilarious, often in their absurdity, such as the one where a competition is organized and part</span>
  <span id="freeText10609971403129329903" style="display:none">Elbow Room by James Alan McPherson<br />9 out of 10<br /><br /><br />Elbow Room is a fantastic collection of stories that has won The Pulitzer Prize, making its great author the first African American to win the coveted award.<br /><br />In the introduction, James Alan McPherson refers to the fact that in the countryside, people have more Elbow Room and this is where most of the stories the place, outside the cities.<br />Most of the tales are hilarious, often in their absurdity, such as the one where a competition is organized and participants are invited to offer solutions for better navigation on a water canal, project for which the most grotesque, pathetic ideas are presented...<br /><br />One inventor wants submerged donkeys to pull the vessels, using some gear to provide air, while they walk on the bottom of the water course, but this proposal is considered to far fetched, for the animals might not see, drag the transport into the side and cause are mayhem.<br />Another participant in the contest suggests that the water must be taken out and railway lines installed at the bottom, only this beats the purpose of the competition and makes no sense, since water is the cheapest means of transportation, to this very day.<br /><br />There are other preposterous concepts, another envisaged a scheme wherein a sort of waterfall would be created, so that gravitation is used, but the plan would involve exorbitant costs and the availability of a few Mississippi rivers.<br />Other tales are amusing in the mistaken identity, or wrong premise, such as the case of the professor who awaits the arrival of candidate to become also a teacher, but who when asked does not the answer to any decent question, thinking for instance that Herodotus is 'something they make with eggs'.<br /><br />This young woman was there to become the cook, not the tutor.<br />Then there is the abominable writer, who kills one character only to forget this act and revive him out of the blue, chapters later, stating that one woman has fluid blue eyes, only to make them black, a few pages later, and generally filling his hopeless work with details that contradict each other.<br /><br />When some women send clothes, socks for charity to Africa, they discover that one warrior dies because of the pants he doesn't know how to wear, while the tribe takes the socks as weapons and then they launch a war against the neighbors...eventually, with more such charity, the whole continent could wage war.<br />All the possible professions have their own narrative, some even have a few, including the undertaker who tries to do more ingenious business with a widow that had seen already four husbands die and thus the supposition is that the latest spouse would not last long either.<br /><br />A gardner takes his gun and kills dogs and cats because he wants to bury them and provide with the poor animals the fertilizer that would make a plant grow with exceptional vigor.<br />There is the man who wants to know the name of the mother in law of...Moses and who keeps asking in the wrong places...besides, it seems that name is unknown, even to experts on the bible.<br /><br />When the gas bill states that he has to pay hundreds of thousands of dollars, the equivalent of many millions today, the infuriated customer argues with the clerk of the company, only to see that the next bill would make the whole of the United States bankrupt.<br />Troubles with a bad tooth are complicated when a gun is used to take it out and a bystander is accidentally shot.<br /><br />A man who lacks a definitive talent for music, makes people think a cow is in terrible pain or somebody has been shot, when he practices.<br />Another character uses the wrong potion and thus his hat is glued to his head, provoking a terrible outburst, and finally condemnation and sentence from the judge who is appalled that he would not take his hat out.<br /><br />However, in charge of the prison is another peculiar personage, the sheriff, who keeps kicking prisoners...out of jail, to their appreciable chagrin, one of them complaining bitterly that he is supposed to be fed and protected, whereas this official sends him out to provide for himself and find shelter wherever possible.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10609971403129329903" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


