<div id="review_2977093293" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2977093293" />
    <a title="Vishnu Brahmandam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8813703-vishnu-brahmandam"><img alt="Vishnu Brahmandam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1488290435p2/8813703.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2977093293?book_show_action=true">Nov 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Vishnu Brahmandam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Vishnu Brahmandam" href="/user/show/8813703-vishnu-brahmandam">Vishnu Brahmandam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8813703-vishnu-brahmandam?shelf=2019">2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2977093293" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer520493727793727897">There are apparently two versions of this book out there. One with the &quot;twelve, rich, thought provocative stories&quot; and another with lots of smaller stories. I&apos;d read the latter and reviewed it below. It makes it rather confusing, them being titled the same way. I&apos;d realized the inconsistency only after I&apos;d reviewed the version I&apos;d read didn&apos;t seem similar to what was going on in some of the other reviews for this book. I&apos;ll try to find the <i>actual</i> 12 stories and review those as well.<br/><br/><b>1. Version wi</b></span>
  <span id="freeText520493727793727897" style="display:none">There are apparently two versions of this book out there. One with the "twelve, rich, thought provocative stories" and another with lots of smaller stories. I'd read the latter and reviewed it below. It makes it rather confusing, them being titled the same way. I'd realized the inconsistency only after I'd reviewed the version I'd read didn't seem similar to what was going on in some of the other reviews for this book. I'll try to find the <i>actual</i> 12 stories and review those as well.<br /><br /><b>1. Version with 31 Chapters (includes Elbow Room)</b><br /><br />Actual rating: ~3.5<br /><br />I love how absolutely weird this whole book was. I spent way too long on the preface because I wasn't entirely sure what I was reading. There was a strangeness that I resonated with too well but also didn't. It was an awkward line to toe between understanding the subtle craziness and wondering if I myself was a little loopy.<br /><br />There is a sort of triumph in relating to strange scenarios that seem out of the ordinary to be completely believable but aren't too far away from the reality of everyday life. Your boss asks you to do something ridiculous enough for you to question your own sanity. The book salesman who tells you the book you're looking for is not only unavailable in his store but doesn't exist in the world. The telemarketer who has what appears to him, a bullet-proof reason on why you need that credit card and how you must take it even if you don't use it because it's free. With that logic, how about I take out pet insurance because there's an offer going on and I might get a pet someday? That actually sounds like something a character from this book would do.<br /><br /><br />The Goodreads description of this book actually explains this satisfactorily, "...examine a world we all know but find difficult to define." This collection of short stories, smoothly hand off the story from one to the other, to show us all the crazy people in this make-believe town. Well, the fictional town which seems familiar in its peculiarity. <br /><br />This book won the Pulitzer Prize for fiction (1978) and it somehow ended up on my radar and onto my list of books to read. The people in these stories seem familiar. They remind me of the strange people I meet and their occasionally (probably more than) ridiculous reasonings. It's not always easy to explain the circumstances we see these people in but the way these stories were told makes it seem like it's more normal than you'd think.<br /><br /> <br />I do believe that everyone needs some elbow room to grow their minds and exercise their imaginative muscles to see the oddities that we ignore in our field of vision. I'm drawing some weird parallel to the way our brains completely ignore our noses even though it's <i>right there</i>. <br />Anyway, I did like these short stories. It's nice to see there are so many people out there with strange whirring minds too.<br /><br /><br /><b>2. The 12 Short Stories</b><br />I could not find all the stories online. I spent hours searching for them and could only find a few. It's scary to think that one day, the books I read will be so out of print that fragments of the stories are only left in the minds of the people who'd read them. <br /><br />The following is the list of the 12 stories. The ones struck-through are the ones I couldn't find. <br /><br />1. Why I Like Country Music <br />2. Story of a Dead Man <br />3. <s>The Silver Bullet </s><br />4. <s> The Faithful </s><br />5. Problems of Art<br />6. The Story of a Scar<br />7. <s> I Am an American </s><br />8. <s> Widows and Orphans </s><br />9. A Loaf of Bread<br />10. <s> Just Enough for the City </s><br />11. <s> A Sense of Story</s><br />12. Elbow Room</span>
  <a data-text-id="520493727793727897" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


