<div id="review_2932184471" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2932184471" />
    <a title="William Reed" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/74963403-william-reed"><img alt="William Reed" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1513266989p2/74963403.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2932184471?book_show_action=true">Aug 10, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="William Reed" class="user" itemprop="url" name="William Reed" href="/user/show/74963403-william-reed">William Reed</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2932184471" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1289176045340899086">This Pulitzer prize winning collection of twelve short stories from the 1970&apos;s tells the story of black Americans as they attempt to come to grips with their variety of experiences living in in America. Though there are times when the stories felt dated, the reading experience was valuable and interesting. Short stories don&apos;t usually stay in my memory as well as longer, more fleshed out novels. <br/><br/>There were three stories that I especially liked. &quot;Why I Like Country Music&quot; tells the story of the na</span>
  <span id="freeText1289176045340899086" style="display:none">This Pulitzer prize winning collection of twelve short stories from the 1970's tells the story of black Americans as they attempt to come to grips with their variety of experiences living in in America. Though there are times when the stories felt dated, the reading experience was valuable and interesting. Short stories don't usually stay in my memory as well as longer, more fleshed out novels. <br /><br />There were three stories that I especially liked. "Why I Like Country Music" tells the story of the narrator reminiscing to his wife how he came to enjoy country music, which was as a fourth grade boy there was a girl in his class, named Gweneth Larson that he fell in love with. The class had the opportunity to do a dance for the school, and the narrator tells how he was able to outwit his class rival, with a little help from his teacher, dance with Gweneth, as the country music played. <br /><br />"The Story of a Scar" is a story that a female narrator tells while she is waiting for her doctor's appointment. She recalls in her younger days she worked in a post office. She had two men, Billy Crawford and Red Bone who were interested in dating her. Each of these men were persistent, and a rivalry grew up between the two. The narrator tells how an unfortunate accident led her to living with the scar that is in the story's title.<br /><br />"A Loaf of Bread" tells about a grocer named Harold Green who has come under criticism because in his grocery stores that he runs across the city he does not charge as much for items in the affluent neighborhoods as he does in poorer, inner city neighborhoods. This has led to his stores being boycotted and him and his family becoming somewhat a pariah in the community. Harold tries to explain the economic reasons for his doing so. <br /><br />As always in a short story collection, some stories work better than others. This book is worth reading because it gives insight to the condition of African Americans as they live, love, and grow. The stories are told with warmth and compassion, and are well written. Why only three stars? A year after reading this book, most of the stories don't stay with me, I can't recall what they were about. I like that McPherson writes stories that turn out in a way that you didn't expect and the characters are not stereotypes. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1289176045340899086" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


