<span id="freeTextContainer16491092317410178583">kind of criminally my first time reading an entire short story collection in a while. <br/><br/>I loved almost all of these. Both the connective tissue between them, and the stark differences in style, tone, voice, content, - are perfectly balanced. <br/><br/>My fave was probably &quot;The Story of a Dead Man&quot; - the dynamic therein is so compelling and juicy, highbrown and lowbrow black culture rubbing up against each other (that dynamic, plus the north / south and even intra-south dynamics of black culture was some of </span>
  <span id="freeText16491092317410178583" style="display:none">kind of criminally my first time reading an entire short story collection in a while. <br /><br />I loved almost all of these. Both the connective tissue between them, and the stark differences in style, tone, voice, content, - are perfectly balanced. <br /><br />My fave was probably "The Story of a Dead Man" - the dynamic therein is so compelling and juicy, highbrown and lowbrow black culture rubbing up against each other (that dynamic, plus the north / south and even intra-south dynamics of black culture was some of the most interesting stuff in here for me). <br /><br />the more conceptual "Just Enough for the City" and title track "Elbow Room" also do really cool stuff that I had never quite seen from short fiction before. <br /><br />will seek out more JAM<br /><br /></span>
